<div id="review_3930537073" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3930537073" />
    <a title="hebe ˘͈ᵕ˘͈" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/122665314-hebe"><img alt="hebe ˘͈ᵕ˘͈" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1625428868p2/122665314.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3930537073?book_show_action=true">Apr 11, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="hebe ˘͈ᵕ˘͈" class="user" itemprop="url" name="hebe ˘͈ᵕ˘͈" href="/user/show/122665314-hebe">hebe ˘͈ᵕ˘͈</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/122665314-hebe?shelf=read-2021">read-2021</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3930537073" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13632165026375580729"><b>june 2021 </b><br/>3.5 ✳︎ this play made me realize that i&apos;m just not a play/drama person, regardless of it being western or eastern. however, for people who do like plays and dramas, i think <i>the peony pavilion</i> would be something you will enjoy and a good glimpse into chinese literature.<br/><br/>like many other romance plays, fictions, and dramas in chinese literature, <i>the peony pavilion</i> explores the conflicts and delicate balance between the concepts of <i>qing</i> and <i>li</i>, or emotions and reason, through a popular genr</span>
  <span id="freeText13632165026375580729" style="display:none"><b>june 2021 </b><br />3.5 ✳︎ this play made me realize that i'm just not a play/drama person, regardless of it being western or eastern. however, for people who do like plays and dramas, i think <i>the peony pavilion</i> would be something you will enjoy and a good glimpse into chinese literature.<br /><br />like many other romance plays, fictions, and dramas in chinese literature, <i>the peony pavilion</i> explores the conflicts and delicate balance between the concepts of <i>qing</i> and <i>li</i>, or emotions and reason, through a popular genre of "scholar and maiden" (才子佳人). the young scholar is usually from a poorer background and standing whereas the maiden is from the aristocratic class with parents who will stand in the way of their union. this play follows the same route with a supernatural twist. <br /><br />what stood out to me the most was not the passionate love of bridal du and liu mengmei that conquered and transcended forces of time, death, and space, but the bitter reality that love (qing) will never "defeat" reason (li), they can only coexist. the irony element in the final chapter was just *chef's kiss*. after everything liu mengmei and bridal du experienced and overcame to be together, the last barrier happens to be society. yes, the living world and its customs and norms. because of this, i didn't view the play to have a "happy ending" but rather an ending where a balance is finally made between qing and li. <br /><br />i can rant on and on about the subtle criticism towards society tang xianzu incorporated into his play (like bridal du becoming a virgin again, etc.) but that's an essay i don't want to write. anyways, i ultimately gave 3.5 stars because i didn't really enjoy the reading process. some scenes were dreadful to read. the plot wasn't particularly interesting either. though, i do think i would like the kunqu performance of <i>the peony pavilion</i> more (i have only seen the performance for <i>union in the shades</i> and i liked it a lot). <br /><br />thanks for reading my two-cent thoughts!<br /><br /><b>april 2021 </b><br />dnf for now ✳︎ i guess my literature class is only reading the first 12 scenes. i’ll have to find time this summer to finish it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13632165026375580729" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


